restrictions, while effective in slowing the spread of the virus, have had impacts on global trade and economy [1]. Ports play a pivotal role in the development of the regional economy as maritime trade accounts for over 80% of global merchandise trade by volume [2]. Hence, it is signiÔ¨Åcant to investigate the impacts of COVID-19 on ship behaviours in the port area during the pandemic, which can be used to estimate the inÔ¨Çuence of COVID-19 on the regional economy, and logistic activities of the port indirectly.
VHF Data Exchange System (VDES) and Automatic IdentiÔ¨Åcation System (AIS) are two leading technologies to broadcast communication in which vessels periodically report their position, course and speed. VDES is on its way to becoming a standard of the International Telecommunication Union. It can implement a more efÔ¨Åcient high-speed data exchange between ships, satellites and shore and protect the AIS from future overload [3]. However, VDES does not have a high penetration now as it is not made mandatory by national authorities and requires a high-cost entry terminal [4]. Therefore, in this study, AIS data is selected to analyze ship behaviours. It includes rich ship motion information, and it is common to use it as Ô¨Åeld data for ship trafÔ¨Åc analysis, trajectories analysis, collision avoidance, etc. [5]‚Äì[7].
Recently, researchers have taken advantage of AIS data to study how COVID-19 interacts with ship activities, port management, and economic conditions [8], [9]. Through the analysis of ship trafÔ¨Åc density over months, COVID-19 impacts could be observed. Nevertheless, these analyses can not quantify the impact of COVID-19 on ship behaviours and port operations. In addition, since economic conditions and other factors affect ship activities, it is hard to distinguish whether the pandemic is the sole cause of variation in ship trafÔ¨Åc volume in analyses that only use one-year historical AIS data as a reference. Missing information in AIS data, such as ship type, berth‚Äôs position, ship arrival time, departure time, also pose challenges. These gaps in knowledge motivate the current analysis of the impacts of COVID-19 on the behaviours of different ships and port operations. Furthermore, such analysis can be used to provide insights for port stakeholders to make tactical decisions.
This paper proposes an analysis method to identify abnormal ship behaviour patterns and quantify the impacts of COVID-19 in the Oslo port area. The discovered knowledge could be used to provide decision supports for stakeholders,

