such as shipping companies, port managers, and policymakers, in the next health emergency crisis. The main contributions are as follows: 1) applying improved density-based spatial clustering of applications with noise by Pythagoras distance (PD-DBSCAN) to identify berths in the Oslo port; 2) employing dynamic time warping (DTW) to analyse ship Ô¨Çow, daily throughout and dwelling time of quays from yearon-year respects, and using signiÔ¨Åcance interval to estimate a COVID-19 impact threshold; 3) performing a short-term impact analysis by combining DTW with statistical analysis from the month-on-month perspective.
The rest of this paper is structured as follows: the next section describes related works on AIS data analysis. Section III details the procedure of knowledge discovery from raw AIS, including data pre-processing, feature extraction, knowledge discovery. Section IV presents the results of three experiments, including berth identiÔ¨Åcation, year-on-year DTW analysis, and month-on-month DTW analysis. Conclusion is given Ô¨Ånally.
II. RELATED WORK
AIS data has been used in maritime transportation for several decades. With the help of satellites, a huge amount of data generated in the process of direct ship-to-ship, ship-to-coast, or coast-to-ship AIS communication can be transmitted to onboard AIS transceivers over long distance. In addition, AIS data contains abundant information, including time-stamp for each recorded data point and the ship‚Äôs Maritime Mobile Service Identity (MMSI), deadweight (DWT), speed over ground (SOG), ship length. This information gives decision-makers extensive knowledge about a ship‚Äôs behaviour and its surroundings. Because it offers rich information in real time, AIS data is widely applied for navigation safety, collision avoidance, trajectory analysis [10].
AIS also has the potential to improve operators‚Äô maritime situational awareness (MSA) and thereby improve navigational safety. Ship trajectories were analysed from AIS data with the help of statistical methods [11]. It contributes to unveiling ship behaviours for abnormal route detection. Wen et al. integrated DBSCAN and ArtiÔ¨Åcial Neural Network to automatically extract ship routes between two ports, and the different routes according to different ships will be designed automatically [12]. For collision avoidance, Gao and Shi proposed a multi-step sub-trajectory clustering analysis method to recognize a unique ship-handling behaviour pattern [13]; Shi and Liu employed a double-gated recurrent unit neural network to learn the collision avoidance pattern hidden in AIS data [14]. It is able to make appropriate collision-avoidance decisions for different maritime navigation statuses in an automatic way. In addition, there are many extended applications of AIS data, such as Ô¨Åshing activities and ship behaviours analysis in restricted waters. For example, Sheng et al. constructed a classiÔ¨Åcation model using a logistic regression technology [15]. It is capable of addressing the classiÔ¨Åcation problem of Ô¨Åshing boats and cargo ships based on their AIS trajectories. Zhang et al. analysed marine trafÔ¨Åc hot-spots, and the spatial-temporal dynamics of ship trafÔ¨Åc in port waters using AIS data [5]. The

analysis could be used for decision-making supports of port operations.
The use of AIS data has broadened in scope, meeting the increasing practical demands, such as trade analysis, port performance evaluation. Zhang et al. proposed an analysis framework to analyse oil trade based on big AIS data [5]. Jia et al. estimated the payloads of vessels using AIS draught data [16]. It is useful to assess vessel utilization, Ô¨Çeet productivity, and subsequent supply and demand conditions in shipping markets. The U.S. Department of Transportation Bureau of Transportation Statistics took advantage of AIS data to analyse the relations between dwell time, vessel size, and container volume [17]. Analysis results made for intelligent port management. Recently, Wang et al. applied ST-DBSCAN to trace ship infection risk and provide a decision support mechanism to prevent and control overseas imported COVID19 cases from international shipping [18]. March et al. used the AIS dataset and SENTINEL 5 data to investigate the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic on marine trafÔ¨Åc patterns within the area and any corresponding changes in the air quality [19]. AIS data was also applied to analyse impacts of COVID-19 pandemic on global trade [20], cruise industry [21], marine trafÔ¨Åc volume reduction [19], container ports [8], transmission path tracking [22], etc. These analyses focus on either the macroscopic trend of the number of different ship types or only one type of ship behaviour literally. They fall short of discovering sufÔ¨Åcient knowledge from AIS data for decision making.
Inspired by the aforementioned studies and considering their limitations, this study proposes an analysis method that is able to identify abnormal patterns and quantify impacts caused by COVID-19 based on AIS data. It is not only suitable for analysing the variation of ship Ô¨Çow but also is generalized to study the variation of daily throughout and dwelling time of ports.
III. SYSTEM STRUCTURE
This section outlines the impacts analysis of COVID-19 on ship behaviours and port operations. The whole analysis procedure is mainly divided into three parts, as shown in Fig. 1. The Ô¨Årst part is data preprocessing, including ship information matching. The second one introduces how several useful features are extracted from raw AIS data. Knowledge discovery process is described in the last part. The analysis results could be used for the decision support of port management and preplanning in the next health emergency crisis.
A. Data Preprocessing
AIS technology could broadcast static ship information and dynamic information at a regular time interval. Onboard transceiver, satellite, and terrestrial base stations exchange information in a real-time way over a long distance. All voyage information of worldwide ships that are equipped with AIS can be tracked and downloaded from marine trafÔ¨Åc,1 marinecadastre.2 In this study, AIS data in the area of Oslo
