in Norway was picked up from 2017 to 2020. The general description of AIS data can be found in [23]. This study focuses on the following attributes: MMSI, longitude, latitude, SOG. Other important information needs to be extracted from AIS data by statistical analysis.
Ship type, deadweight, ship destination, arrival time, and berthing time are extremely important for the analysis of the impact of COVID-19 on ship behaviours. Sea-web,3 marine trafÔ¨Åc,1 and myshiptracking4 is accessed to match ship type and deadweight information based on MMSI. In the next step, ship types need to be changed into numerical values for the sake of the convenience of data analysis. Numbers from ‚Äò1‚Äô to ‚Äò6‚Äô were assigned to ‚ÄòCargo,‚Äô ‚ÄòCarrier,‚Äô ‚ÄòContainer,‚Äô ‚ÄòTanker,‚Äô ‚ÄòCruise,‚Äô ‚ÄòFerry,‚Äô respectively. Other ship types, such as yacht and Ô¨Åshing vessels, are excluded in this study.
B. Feature Extraction
To obtain the ship arrival time and its berthing time, it is necessary to pinpoint the ship‚Äôs destination, i.e. berth. To this end, position points (Latitude, Longitude) with ‚ÄòSOG = 0‚Äô are selected. ‚ÄòSOG = 0‚Äô means ship is mooring. However, ships may moor at a position at the outside of a berth. In order to address this problem, a clustering approach is introduced to identify real berths. DBSCAN has the ability to determine clusters by grouping together points that are closer. Unlike K-means, which require predeÔ¨Åned k clusters, DBSCAN can
3https://maritime.ihs.com/ 4https://www.myshiptracking.com/vessels

identify the number of clusters automatically [24], [25]. There-

fore, DBSCAN is selected to identify berths in this study.

Studies using DBSCAN generally employ Euclidean dis-

tance to compute the distance between data points. Never-

theless, it does not work very well for distance computation

of AIS data points because of the scale of geographical

coordinates. SpeciÔ¨Åcally, the numerical precision of latitude

and longitude is six digits after the decimal point. Although

a ship is far away from another one in the real world,

their Euclidean distance computed by coordinates is quite

close to zero, such as 0.0001. This leads to the intractable

selection of a proper distance threshold () according to the

true distance among berths. In other words, the selection

of  is time-consuming. Therefore, this study proposed an

improved clustering algorithm (PD-DBSCAN) that replaces

Euclidean distance with Pythagoras distance. It is able to

transfer coordinate system distance to geographic distance. It is

convenient to determine a proper  based on the actual distance

between berths. For example, if two berths are as far away as

400 meters,  is supposed to be selected as 200 meters half of

the berths‚Äô distance. The Pythagoras formula is shown in (1).

