The pseudocode of PD-DBSCAN is shown in Algorithm 1. This algorithm is mainly made up of three parts: 1) Ô¨Ånding neighbours of each point and identifying core points; 2) adding

neighbouring core points into clusters and ignoring non-core points; 3) assigning each non-core point to a nearby cluster if the cluster is a neighbour, otherwise assigning it to noise. There are two important parameters that need to be predeÔ¨Åned. They are distance threshold () and density threshold (minPts). Therein,  is used to Ô¨Ånd neighbours of each point; minPts is used for judging whether this cluster has more than minPts points. As a consequence, the selection of  and minPts affects the accuracy of clustering results directly. A more detailed introduction can be found in [25].
After berth identiÔ¨Åcation, to reduce the complexity of data analysis, all berths are grouped into different quays based on their position and functions. Next, the arrival time and dwelling time of a ship need to be determined. The time identiÔ¨Åcation of ships is carried out one after the other. Fig. 2 shows the schematic diagram regarding how to compute the arrival time, departure time, and dwelling time of a ship. Owing to a ship calling the quays several times a year, multiple time tables are obtained from AIS data. Therein, ‚ÄòAD,‚Äô ‚Äò AH ,‚Äô ‚ÄòD D,‚Äô and ‚ÄòD H ‚Äô denotes ‚Äòarrival date,‚Äô ‚Äòarrival hour,‚Äô ‚Äòdeparture date,‚Äô and ‚Äòdeparture hour‚Äô separately. Iteration is performed to Ô¨Ånd the Ô¨Årst data point with ‚ÄòS OG < 0.1.‚Äô If this point is inside the berth area, the current time-stamp is recorded as ‚Äò A Di , A Hi .‚Äô Next, the data point moves to the next one until its ‚ÄòS OG ‚â• 0.2.‚Äô Meanwhile, the time stamp is recorded as ‚ÄòD Di , D Hi .‚Äô In the following step, the ship‚Äôs dwelling time is calculated by ‚Äò24 √ó (D Di ‚àí A Di ) + (D Hi ‚àí A Hi).‚Äô After that, a new time table could be derived from original time tables. Next, time calibration is used to check whether the current dwelling time could be merged with the last one. For example, if ‚ÄòD Di = A Di+1‚Äô and ‚ÄòD Hi < D Hi+1,‚Äô i th and (i + 1)th dwelling time should be added up together. (i + 1)th arrival time is substituted by i th arrival time while i th record is removed. This process is repeated until the last data point

