C. Knowledge Discovery
This section aims to discover knowledge from processed AIS data. To this end, a similarity measuring method is selected to carry out abnormal pattern recognition. Next, it is combined with statistical analysis to analyse behaviour patterns of ships under COVID-19 effects. The impact analysis is mainly composed of long-term analysis and short-term analysis. The long-term impact analysis aims to investigate the year-on-year difference caused by COVID-19 and derive an impact threshold for the following short-term analysis. The short-term impact analysis estimates the variation of monthon-month impact and explores the trend based on historical knowledge.
In order to demonstrate the ability of the proposed method to discover abnormal patterns caused by COVID-19, Oxford Stringency Index (OSI) is introduced [26]. This is a composite index by recording policies on a scale to reÔ¨Çect the extent of government action. The OSI ranges from 0 to 100 and increases over time if more stringent mitigation policies are implemented or decrease if policies are rescinded. Four-year historical AIS data from 2017 to 2020 is used to make a comparison of ship Ô¨Çow. If some abnormal patterns could be detected and coincide with OSI trend, that shows the proposed method holds for impacts analysis of COVID-19 on ship behaviours. Then it is used for long-term and shorttime trend analysis of ship Ô¨Çow volume. For long-term impact analysis, a signiÔ¨Åcance interval test is used to determine an impact threshold for the following analysis. If the impact is larger than the threshold, it is regarded as a severe impact caused by the pandemic. The short-term analysis is employed to study the varying trend of ship Ô¨Çow volume over each month against the past several months. Such analysis makes it possible for stakeholders to observe the short-term variations and estimate the future trend. The obtained knowledge could be used for intelligent port management and preplanning in the next pandemic crisis.
This study is mainly to compare the ship Ô¨Çow in different years to quantify the impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic. The extracted frequency of ships accessing a port is a time-varying variable. Compared with other time-series data with high sampling frequency like electroencephalography [27], trafÔ¨Åc Ô¨Çow of car [28], it has a feature of sparseness, as its timestamp is ‚Äòday.‚Äô Therefore, machine learning and deep learning are not suitable for this case as they require a remarkably large data set. Since ship Ô¨Çow variation could be treated as a time-series sequence, the similarity of different years‚Äô sequences could be counted as the impact of COVID-19. If the similarity is lower, the impact is greater, and vice versa. The most straightforward similarity measure for time series is L p-norms such as L1 (Manhattan), L2 (Euclidean). However, since the mapping requires data points to be one-to-one correspondence, they are sensitive to misalignments and length of the sequence in time and are incapable of handling local time-shifting [29]. As a consequence, it is necessary to introduce a similarity measure

