IV. CASE STUDY
This section introduces three experiments regarding how to employ AIS data in Oslo to analyse the impacts of COVID-19

A. Berth IdentiÔ¨Åcation
This study uses four years of historical AIS data from 2017 to 2020, in the Oslo area. The data with ‚ÄòSOG > 0‚Äô is removed. The total remaining data volume is over twenty million. It is impossible to employ all data to cluster berths. As a consequence, the data needs re-sampling to reduce the training cost. SpeciÔ¨Åcally, each vessel is re-sampled by ten samples for each year. There are 11170 samples in total. minPts is selected from the interval [20, 100].  is in the interval [100, 500]. Their physical meanings are the minimum number of ships in a berth and the short distance between berths.
Fig. 3 shows the clustering results based on different combinations of minPts and . Through the analysis of clustering results, all berths could be identiÔ¨Åed correctly when the number of clusters reaches around 30. If the number is less than 30, that indicates some berths are merged together. As long as the clusters are within [20, 30], the analysis is not inÔ¨Çuenced because all berths are grouped into different quays based on their position and functionality. In order to display the berths in detail, the value of (30, 200) is picked up as the parameters‚Äô value of (minPts, ) separately as shown in the annotation of Fig. 3.
For the convenience of investigating port operations, the identiÔ¨Åed berths are grouped into different quays. As shown

