like cargo, carrier, container, and tanker have small variations before and during COVID-19, while cruise and ferry have a large variation. It shows that the inÔ¨Çuence of the global pandemic on passenger ships aligns with the general drop in leisure travel.
Fig. 6(a)‚àºFig. 6(c) shows the DTW and LCSS analysis results of comparing the ferry Ô¨Çow in 2020 with the Ô¨Çow in 2017, 2018, 2019. The color bar represents the value of OSI, which increased from the beginning of March and reached a peak at the end of March. Then it remained stable until the end of April. It went to a low level in June and stayed relatively Ô¨Çat until the middle of November. At that point, it rose again. The blue dotted line denotes there is no difference regarding the ferry‚Äôs Ô¨Çow between two years. In other words, the ferry‚Äôs Ô¨Çow of each day in different years are the same. Black curves represent the difference in different years. As two sequences do not vary synchronously, that leads to a position deviation against the diagonal line when DTW and LCSS are matching the most similar positions. The horizontal line appears in the path, which indicates a drastic variation in the corresponding period. Results show DTW is more sensitive to capture the ferry‚Äôs Ô¨Çow difference as soon as the COVID pandemic started in the beginning of March. Therefore, DTW is leveraged to analyse the impacts of COVID-19 in the following experiments.
Fig. 8 shows almost identical, varying trends of ferries Ô¨Çow in separate comparisons of 2017 with 2018, 2017 with 2019, and 2018 with 2019. As ship Ô¨Çows in different years are not synchronized completely, it is unsurprising that these sequences have some differences. In Fig. 6(a)‚àºFig. 6(c), the

big change appears from March to July as a result of the number of ferries decreasing drastically. After July, with the increasing number of ferry, the difference becomes lower gradually. This trend is in line with the change of OSI. The result shows DTW is capable of identifying abnormal ship behaviour patterns. Other than abnormal pattern identiÔ¨Åcation, DTW could tell us which ship types have stronger resilience to the onset of the global pandemic as well. For example, Fig. 7(a)‚àºFig. 7(c) and Fig. 9 show the comparison of general cargo‚Äôs Ô¨Çow among four years. There is no evident change in the DTW path, which means the inÔ¨Çuence COVID-19 is small.
DTW path only reveals the relative trend change between two time-series sequences. In order to better analyse the impacts of COVID-19 to ship Ô¨Çow and port operations, DTW distance computed by (3) is leveraged to quantify impacts. As discussed above, even though in years without COVID19, the difference of ship Ô¨Çow still exists due to uncertain factors. Therefore, average variation of ship Ô¨Çow, throughout, and berthing time is regarded as a benchmark value before 2020. The variation during 2020 deducting average value is seen as an impact caused by COVID-19.
DTW analysis results are shown in Table II. The units of DTW distance with respect to ship‚Äôs Ô¨Çow, daily throughout of quays, and berthing time are the number of times, 10000 tons, and 100 hours separately. ‚ÄòAverage variation‚Äô is the average value of the former three-year variations. ‚Äò VS Y‚Äô20‚Äô denotes ‚Äò2017 vs. 2020,‚Äô ‚Äò2018 vs. 2020,‚Äô ‚Äò2019 vs. 2020.‚Äô ‚Äò(%)‚Äô denotes the increasing percentage of current value against the benchmark. For example, 2.4% represents the variation between 2017 and 2020 rises by 2.4% against the average variation. That also means the impact caused by COVID-19 is about 2.4%. On the other hand, ‚àí9.7% means the variation caused by COVID-19 is less than the average variation. In other words, COVID-19 does not inÔ¨Çuence its behaviours.
The mined knowledge is shown as follows:
‚Ä¢ The drastic variation appears in the Ô¨Çow of cruise and ferry as a result of the big decrease of ship frequencies.
‚Ä¢ Cargo ships are inÔ¨Çuenced slightly. ‚Ä¢ Most of port operations are not affected heavily. ‚Ä¢ Quay 3 has a signiÔ¨Åcant change with respect to daily
throughout and berthing time before and during the pandemic.
The Ô¨Årst point indicates that passenger ships are sensitive to the global pandemic. That brings revelations to policy-makers that service industries are supposed to gain more Ô¨Ånancial supports. The second point implies port managers should guarantee the sufÔ¨Åcient cargo handling capability of quays to speed up logistics. The third point tells us that few ships were stopping this berth during COVID-19. This is a rational outcome, possibly because quay 3 is close to ferry berths and at Oslo port centre. Therefore cargo ships are moved to other cargo quays. There are some abnormal patterns that are not caused by COVID-19. For example, the variation of carrier‚Äôs Ô¨Çow is quite large (81.6%) between 2019 and 2020. That mainly results from the decrease of carrier‚Äôs frequency in 2019 as shown in Table I.

