COVID-19 impacts rather than the accurate COVID-19 impact estimation. From our case studies, the proposed method is efÔ¨Åcient to analyze the impacts of COVID-19 to ship activities. In addition, the OSI is a composite index to reÔ¨Çect the inÔ¨Çuence of COVID-19 and its variation is not identical to the variation of ship activities completely. For example, as shown in Fig. 6(a), the risk level rose slightly again since November while the ferry‚Äôs Ô¨Çow did not have a signiÔ¨Åcant decrease. As a whole, results show the abnormal pattern discovered by DTW can match the variation of OSI well.
Another one arises from the subjectivity of the clustering analysis. The identiÔ¨Åcation of berths is based on PD-DBSCAN and its number is chosen subjectively. In this study, 32 berths are identiÔ¨Åed by PD-DBSCAN as shown in Fig. 3. It is reasonable that the number of berths is within [20, 32] because adjacent berths are merged. In addition, as berths are grouped into different quays based on their positions as shown in Fig. 5, therefore, the analysis of port operational efÔ¨Åciency is

inÔ¨Çuenced by way of quay grouping to some extent. For real applications, users can adjust the partition of quays according to practical demands.
In a word, case studies veriÔ¨Åed that the proposed approach could analyze the impacts of COVID-19 to ship behaviours and port operations efÔ¨Åciently.
V. CONCLUSION
This paper proposed an analysis approach to estimate COVID-19 impacts on ship activities. In order to verify the feasibility of the proposed method, AIS data in the Oslo area is taken as an example. Improved DBSCAN (PD-DBSCAN) is leveraged to identify berths. Based on the identiÔ¨Åed berths, ship arrival time and berthing time can be determined. After features are extracted from raw AIS data, DTW is compared with LCSS to verify its performance in terms of abnormal pattern recognition. Next, DTW is employed to detect abnormal patterns and quantify the impacts of COVID-19. After that,

